Many of the predictors are Characters. Category describes what the object being auctioned is. SellerRating takes integer values. endDay takes the name of the day of the day the auction concluded. Competitive is the outcome variable we want to classify by. Competitive. equal to 1 is the dominant class, basic classificators will tend to classify cases as belonging to this class.

summary(df2$Competitive==1)
##    Mode   FALSE    TRUE 
## logical     906    1066
# set the character variables as factors
# we do this now, otherwise the functions boosting and bagging cannot work
df2[,c(1,2,5,8)] <- lapply(df2[,c(1,2,5,8)], as.factor)

The class that appears the most often is Competitive==1, we will set it as the positive class.

Partition the data:

set.seed(1234) # to randomly select the records that will make up the samples, and get the same samples when we re-run the code
training<- sample(row.names(df2), 0.6*dim(df2)[1]) # 60% of records makeup the training set
validation <- setdiff(row.names(df2), training ) # 40% the validation set, all records not previously sorted in the training set
train.df<- df2[training,] #in data.frame format
valid.df<- df2[validation,] #in data.frame format

Classification Tree

13.2.a

options(scipen = 999)
set.seed(1234) # make it replicable
ebay_t <- rpart(Competitive. ~ ., data = train.df, method = "class")
length(ebay_t$frame$var[ebay_t$frame$var == "<leaf>"]) # how many end nodes
## [1] 12
rpart.plot(ebay_t, yesno = TRUE, digits =-3) # plot the tree

The tree has 12 end leaves.

ebay_pred <- predict(ebay_t, valid.df, type="class") # predict classification
ebay_prob<- predict(ebay_t, valid.df, type = "prob") # predict probabilities of classification
ebay_cf<- confusionMatrix(ebay_pred, valid.df$Competitive., positive = "1") # build confusion matrix
ebay_cf$overall[1]# accuracy
##  Accuracy 
## 0.8314322
ebay_cf$byClass[c(1,2)] # Sensitivity and specificity
## Sensitivity Specificity 
##   0.7869249   0.8803191
fourfoldplot(ebay_cf$table, color = c("red", "pink"))

  • The accuracy measure for the classification the tree conducts amounts to 83%

Sensitivity=A/(A+C) Specificity = D/(B+D)

  • Sensitivity tells us how good is our model at detecting records belonging to the psoitive class, which in our case is 1. It amounts to 78% of correctly classified records belonging to class competitive=1.
  • Specificity tells us how exact the assignment to class 1 (the positive one) is, in this case it is exact in 88% of the cases.

Lift Chart

A lift chart helps us understand how successful our model was in classifying. It does so by ordering the observed values of the outcome variable (Competitive.) by the decreasing probabilities our model predicted (table 5.6). We then spit this ordered set into deciles, so to have a top decile, which the most successful in terms of how many responders or what other class is our class of interest.

In our case is the most competitive decile.

source: (https://select-statistics.co.uk/blog/cumulative-gains-and-lift-curves-measuring-the-performance-of-a-marketing-campaign/)

we use methods from caret package document on moodle: (http://topepo.github.io/caret/measuring-performance.html#lift-curves)

#new dataset with the variables needed in the lift function, otherwise the function searches within the environment
# select the predicted probabilities for competitive.=1
lift_results<- data.frame(true_class = valid.df$Competitive., prob = ebay_prob[,2])

lift_obj <- lift(relevel(as.factor(true_class), ref="1") ~ prob, data = lift_results) #to plot our lift curve (figure 5.6)
# the lift_results are ordered by the predicted probabilities 
# each value is treated as cut point
# number of samples with observed competitive.=1 are determined
# lift computed as the ratio of the % of samples in each split for y=1 over the same % in the entire set

gain_table <- gains(actual = as.numeric(as.character(lift_results$true_class)),predicted = lift_results$prob, groups=dim(lift_results)[1])
# we build the table alike table 5.6, we turn the outcome variable into numeric, so that we can compute cumulative sums
# actual response values, turned into their corresponding numeric values and predictions

dec_gain <- gains(actual = as.numeric(as.character(lift_results$true_class)), predicted= lift_results$prob, groups = 10,ties.method=c("first")) 
# figure 5.7
# groups in this case at default value 10, we are computing deciles

deciles<- dec_gain$mean.resp / mean(as.numeric(as.character(lift_results$true_class)))
# mean response in decile/ "average" class in all observations

par(mfrow=c(1,2)) #organise space
plot(lift_obj, values = 60, auto.key = list(columns = 1,lines = TRUE, points = T)) # plot releveled lift curve

barplot(deciles, names.arg = dec_gain$depth, xlab = "Percentile", ylab = "Mean Response", main = "Decile-wise lift chart") #decile chart

The ideal lift chart would trace the top perimeter of the grey area. The chart seems to demonstrate that our pruned tree seems to classify well enough. Which is in line with the 0.831 accuracy measure from the confusion matrix.

TopDecileLift(lift_results$prob, valid.df$Competitive.) # compute the lift for the top decile
## [1] 1.862

The lift in the top decile amounts to 1.86. A lift of 1 would mean no improvement in classifying with the model is achieved, and that randomly selecting records would yield equivalent results.

Boosting

13.2.b

Boosting fits multiple trees, so to draw samples that give higher selection probabilities to mis-classified records, and fit new trees on these new samples. This process is repeated multiple times, and the weights are updated so to give more importance to the mis-classified records.

set.seed(1234) #make the process replicable
boosting <- boosting(Competitive. ~ ., data = train.df)
boost_pred<- predict(boosting, valid.df, type="class")# predict class
boost_prob<- predict(boosting, valid.df, type="prob") # predict probabilities
boost_cf <- confusionMatrix(as.factor(boost_pred$class), valid.df$Competitive., positive = "1")# table 13.1
boost_cf$overall[1] # accuracy
##  Accuracy 
## 0.8846641
boost_cf$byClass[c(1,2)] # Sensitivity and specificity
## Sensitivity Specificity 
##   0.8765133   0.8936170
fourfoldplot(boost_cf$table, color = c("red", "pink")) # plot matrix

Compared to the first tree, accuracy measure has increased, 88% of predictions are correct . Detection of records belonging of the first class has improved as well, Sensitivity and Specificity are respectively 87% and 89%. Boosted Tree approach produced more accurate categorization.

# repeat process to build lift, gain chart as before
boost_results<- data.frame(true_class = valid.df$Competitive., prob = boost_prob$prob[,2])

lift_boost <- lift(relevel(as.factor(true_class), ref="1") ~ prob, data = lift_results) 

gain_table_boost <- gains(actual = as.numeric(as.character(boost_results$true_class)),predicted = boost_results$prob, groups=dim(boost_results)[1])
## Warning in gains(actual = as.numeric(as.character(boost_results$true_class)), :
## Warning: Fewer distinct predicted values than groups requested
dec_gain_boost <- gains(actual = as.numeric(as.character(boost_results$true_class)), predicted= boost_results$prob, groups = 10,ties.method=c("first")) 

deciles_boost<- dec_gain_boost$mean.resp / mean(as.numeric(as.character(boost_results$true_class)))

par(mfrow=c(1,2)) #organise space
plot(lift_boost, values = 60, auto.key = list(columns = 1,lines = TRUE, points = T))

barplot(deciles_boost, names.arg = dec_gain_boost$depth, xlab = "Percentile", ylab = "Mean Response", main = "Decile-wise lift chart")

TopDecileLift(boost_results$prob, valid.df$Competitive.) # compute the lift for the top decile
## [1] 1.91

The lift curve is now closer to the ideal shape, consequently, the lift of the top decile has increased as well to 1.91.

Bagging

13.1.c

The process generates multiple random samples (with replacement), then runs an algorithm over these samples and produces scores.

set.seed(1234)
bagging<- bagging(Competitive. ~ ., data = train.df)
bag_pred<- predict(bagging, valid.df, type="class") # classes
bag_prob<- predict(bagging, valid.df, type="prob")  # probabilities
bag_cf <- confusionMatrix(as.factor(bag_pred$class), valid.df$Competitive., positive = "1")

fourfoldplot(bag_cf$table, color = c("red", "pink")) #plot confusion matrix

bag_cf$overall[1] # Accuracy
##  Accuracy 
## 0.8441065
bag_cf$byClass[c(1,2)] # Sensitivity and specificity
## Sensitivity Specificity 
##   0.8329298   0.8563830

Accuracy measure is higher than original model, but not as high as the boosted tree, the value is 84%. The byClass statistics describe a less successful model as well.

#Repeat process for lift chart
bag_results<- data.frame(true_class = valid.df$Competitive., prob = bag_prob$prob[,2])

lift_bag <- lift(relevel(as.factor(true_class), ref="1") ~ prob, data = bag_results) #to plot our lift curve


gain_table_bag <- gains(actual = as.numeric(as.character(bag_results$true_class)),predicted = bag_results$prob, groups=dim(bag_results)[1])

dec_gain_bag<- gains(actual = as.numeric(as.character(bag_results$true_class)), predicted= bag_results$prob, groups = 10,ties.method=c("first")) 

deciles_bag<- dec_gain_bag$mean.resp / mean(as.numeric(as.character(bag_results$true_class)))

par(mfrow=c(1,2)) #organise space
plot(lift_bag, values = 60, auto.key = list(columns = 1,lines = TRUE, points = T))

barplot(deciles_bag, names.arg = dec_gain_bag$depth, xlab = "Percentile", ylab = "Mean Response", main = "Decile-wise lift chart")

TopDecileLift(bag_results$prob, valid.df$Competitive.) # compute the lift for the top decile
## [1] 1.91

Accuracy wise Boosted seems to perform slightly better. Overall, both models display improved classification performance. The lift given by the 2 improved models seems to be the same between thought. This tells us that the mis-classification for the bagging process happens for higher deciles of the population.

Random Forest

13.2.d

Random Forest uses bootstrap sampling as well. In this case the sample over which we fit trees over, are random. It then combines the predictions to obtain a improved classification performance.

set.seed(1234)
rand_f <- randomForest(Competitive. ~ ., data = train.df, mtry=4, importance = T)
varImpPlot(rand_f, type=1) # we print out the variable importance plot too

rand_pred<- predict(rand_f, valid.df, type="class") # predict class
rand_prob<- predict(rand_f, valid.df, type="prob")  # predict prob
rand_cf <- confusionMatrix(as.factor(rand_pred), valid.df$Competitive., positive = "1")

fourfoldplot(rand_cf$table, color = c("red", "pink")) # plot confusion matrix

rand_cf$overall[1] # Accuracy
## Accuracy 
## 0.878327
rand_cf$byClass[c(1,2)] # Sensitivity and specificity
## Sensitivity Specificity 
##   0.8813559   0.8750000

Random Forests permits us to also print a plot of importance of predictors. Close Price and Open Price are the most important features in the classification process Random Forests runs.

In terms of accuracy Random forests is almost as well performing as the boosted process,it does a better job at detecting positive class records. Specificity is lower instead.

#Repeat process for lift chart
rand_results<- data.frame(true_class = valid.df$Competitive., prob = rand_prob[,2])

lift_rand <- lift(relevel(as.factor(true_class), ref="1") ~ prob, data = rand_results) #to plot our lift curve


gain_table_rand <- gains(actual = as.numeric(as.character(rand_results$true_class)),predicted = rand_results$prob, groups=dim(rand_results)[1])
## Warning in gains(actual = as.numeric(as.character(rand_results$true_class)), :
## Warning: Fewer distinct predicted values than groups requested
dec_gain_rand<- gains(actual = as.numeric(as.character(rand_results$true_class)), predicted= rand_results$prob, groups = 10,ties.method=c("first")) 

deciles_rand<- dec_gain_rand$mean.resp / mean(as.numeric(as.character(rand_results$true_class)))

par(mfrow=c(1,2)) #organise space
plot(lift_rand, values = 60, auto.key = list(columns = 1,lines = TRUE, points = T))

barplot(deciles_rand, names.arg = dec_gain_rand$depth, xlab = "Percentile", ylab = "Mean Response", main = "Decile-wise lift chart")

options(digits = 3)
TopDecileLift(rand_results$prob, valid.df$Competitive.) # compute the lift for the top decile
## [1] 1.91

For all 3 processes the lift in the first decile is the same, again this tells us that the first decile is classified equally well by the models, but given the differences in accuracy measures, most likely issues incur with later deciles.

Bagged Tree vs Random Forest

13.2.d

Random Forests can be described as an ensemble of bagged trees.The main difference is that in fitting classification Random Forests uses a random subset of predictors. In bagging the predictors are always the same! Voting is used for classification in both methods, same goes for averaging for prediction.

accuracies<- data.frame("Methods"= c("Bagging", "Random Forests"), "Accuracy"= c(bag_cf$overall[1], rand_cf$overall[1])) #accuracies
ggplot(accuracies) + geom_col(aes(x=Methods,y= Accuracy, fill=Accuracy), show.legend = F)+ theme_classic()+ ggtitle("Comparison of Bagging and Random Forests") #comparison

Random Forests seems to perform better in terms of Accuracy, and Specificity and Sensitivity. In this sense the ensemble of bagged trees improves the quality of our predictions.
